 When I first looked at the task manager project codebase, I understanding of it was basic. Due to being familiar with coding, I was able to see that Node.js was used. In this project users can use CRUD(Create, Read, Update and Delete) in tasks. It uses commander for CLI commands and stores data in a JSON file. The main parts of the project were the Task, Taskpriority, TastStatus, Task manager and TaskStorage but I saw these classes as separate pieces while doing a simple job. I thought it was a basic tracker where task was saves, filtered and displayed without thinking much about the structure of the code
As we continued with learning the code with the prompts, my understanding became much clearer and structured. I started to see that the system is not just a simple task list but rather a workflow system. The task represents a task that moves through different stages like TODO, IN_PROGRESS, REVIEW and DONE. The task status is not just a label but rather the progress of the task. The task priority helps decide what is more important and TaskStorage is a simple database that saves and loads tasks. Taskmanager is the brain behind everything. This helped me understand that the code is dtructured in layers and each layer had a responsibility

The most helpful part of the learning process was when I was asked to explain things in simple business terms instead of just reading the code. This made me think about what each concept means in real life. For example, I Learned that isOverdue() is not just checking dates but is about identifying delayed work that might affect other tasks. I also understood that priority is not about permission or approval but about deciding what should be done first when time and resources are limited. Another useful insight was seeing how the system flows. The CLI uses user input, TaskManager applies rules, TaskStorage saves data and Task represents the actual work item. This made the more system easier to understand
When thinking about the new business rule that marks tasks as abandoned if they are overdure for more than seven days unless they are high priority. I learned to first treat it as a business rule rather than just a coding change. I realised this rule affects the way tasks behave over time not just how they are displayed because of this; the main logic should be inside the TaskManager since it handles the business rules. I would also need to add a new status called abandoned is TaskStatus because it represents a new stage in the task lifecycle. The rule would work by checking all tasks, seeing which ones are overdue for more than 7 days and then updating their status if they are not high priority
From this experience, I also learned a better way to approach unfamiliar codebases. Instead of jumping straight into searching for keywords, it is better to first understand what the system is trying to do. Once I understand the goal of the system, I can identify the main parts like user input, business logic, data storage and domain models. After that it helps to follow one complete flow such as creating tasks from start to finish to see how everything connects. Only after building this mental picture does the searching through code becomes useful. I also found it helpful to write down simple definitions of important concepts so that I don’t confuse their meanings later

Overall this approach helped me move from just reading code to understand how the system works. It made the codebases feel less like separate files and more like a connected system that represents real world work and processes


